{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":157397,"duration_api_ms":140613,"num_turns":16,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"0a49340b-2cbb-4f4b-8a8a-6599d0458953","total_cost_usd":0.8510489999999999,"usage":{"input_tokens":13,"cache_creation_input_tokens":66122,"cache_read_input_tokens":563443,"output_tokens":6240,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":66122,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":13,"outputTokens":6240,"cacheReadInputTokens":563443,"cacheCreationInputTokens":66122,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.8510489999999999,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Reviewed the diff implementing idempotent completion retry with lineage-based snapshot reconciliation and journal deduplication. All 667 tests pass. The core correctness of the crash-recovery flow is sound: lineage is the source of truth, snapshot is recomputed from it, and journal events are deduplicated. Found one material correctness concern and one significant maintainability risk.","amendments":[{"body":"In `update_task_run` (service.rs:590), `snapshot.updated_at` is set to `finalized_run.finished_at.unwrap_or(finished_at)`, which on a replay uses the ORIGINAL completion timestamp, not the current wall clock. If any other operation updated the snapshot between the failed attempt and the retry, `updated_at` would regress to an earlier value. Fix: use `snapshot.updated_at.max(finished_at)` or take `max(finalized_run.finished_at.unwrap_or(finished_at), snapshot.updated_at)` so the timestamp never moves backward.","rationale":"A backward-moving `updated_at` could confuse any consumer that relies on monotonically increasing snapshot timestamps (e.g., cache invalidation or staleness checks). The window is narrow but the fix is trivial."},{"body":"`normalize_task_runs` + `task_runs_same_attempt` + `merge_task_run_attempt` in service.rs (lines 134-191) duplicate `collapse_runs_for_bead` + `same_attempt` + `merge_attempt_rows` in fs.rs (lines 2301-2407). The only difference is that `collapse_runs_for_bead` also filters by bead_id. Extract the shared merge/normalize logic into a single location (e.g., a function on TaskRunEntry or a helper module) and have both call sites use it, to prevent the two copies from silently diverging.","rationale":"Two independent implementations of the same start/terminal merge algorithm is a correctness risk: a bug fix or behavioral change in one copy will easily be missed in the other, leading to snapshot reconciliation disagreeing with bead-level queries."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"f48f7a2c-cd1c-4101-91ac-1e83c8ed8e07"}
